@NODE "mail_0" " #8000000B "
From: amorel <amorel@...>
Date: 11-23-01 00:40:12
Subject: @{b}#8000000B@{ub}

I keep getting this guru for some odd unknown reason. In both blitz versions.
The guru says "trying to read 68881/2 fpu opcodes on a system without that
fpu" I do have a 040 which has a different fpu, but I do NOT use any fpu
code whatsoever. This also seems to have started to happen when I started
implementing saving a file to disk. If it happens it mainly happens right or
soon after saving a file. Not always though.

I also get at these occasions some #80000003 gurus and #80000005 iirc but not
as often.

I can`t discover any errors in the save routine, I open the file correctly and
only save if it opened ok, then I close it. I use lotanlib IO functions like
writenm etc.


Function savesong{}
SHARED savexy
SHARED *songs
SHARED *mysongs
SHARED songnumber

  result.b=NFalse

  songnaam$=aslfilerequest_{"Save Song",ProgDir$,"song1","#?",NTrue,NFalse}

  *file1.l=OpenF(&songnaam$,#MODE_READWRITE)
  If *file1
    result=NTrue
    FSeek *file1,0,1

  ;set the list position and use +1 to set it correctly
    SET_LIST_POS{*songs,songnumber+1}

    rc=WriteNM(*file1,*mysongs\songnr,1)
    rc=WriteCH(*file1,*mysongs\songname)
    rc=WriteNM(*file1,*mysongs\songlength,0)

    ;etcetera
    ;....

    CloseF *file1

  EndIf

  Function Return result

End Function


Any ideas?

Regards

-- 
