@NODE "mail_10" " Re: 2/0?? "
From: Sami Näätänen <sami.naatanen@...>
Date: 11-10-01 08:03:09
Subject: @{b}Re: 2/0??@{ub}

amorel wrote:

> On 09-Nov-01, DAVID MCMINN (9429210) wrote:
> 
> C=I'm confused now, does it happen when you are compiling or when the
> C=program is running? And does it happen anywhere you use the var, e.g.
> C=varname=5 or does it only crash on the lines where you are dividing by
> C=zero?
> 
> As I said when compiling. But quite a while into the compiling process, the
> compiling window is still there though. Try it out I`d say. Just change a var
> you use in a prog(maybe used in an os funtcion) to 2/0 or so and see what
> happens. It`s a suspend/bopot type of guru so you won`t take your system down
> right away.


Very simple answer.

What the compiler does for stuff like "4+5+12445-3/4" it evaluates the 
value, which it then puts to the code it produces.
So what it does for "2/0" it evaluat... hey wait a minute it needs to 
divide by zero ;)





---------------------------------------------------------------------
@ENDNODE

@NODE "mail_11" " Re: 2/0?? "
From: amorel <amorel@...>
Date: 11-16-01 04:59:27
Subject: @{b}Re: 2/0??@{ub}

On 10-Nov-01, Sami Näätänen wrote:

C=What the compiler does for stuff like "4+5+12445-3/4" it evaluates the 
C=value, which it then puts to the code it produces.
C=So what it does for "2/0" it evaluat... hey wait a minute it needs to 
C=divide by zero ;)

I see :-)
But I think something else has been found out, perhaps obvious and known by
most, I don`t know. That is that it doesn`t seem to evaluate or even put
variables in the resulting binary if it is not used in any commands/functions
etc. Should be a standard feature of a compiler though, I guess.

Regards

