@NODE "mail_97" " Re: An idea for screen/window/gadget usage "
From: David McMinn <dave@...>
Date: 11-24-01 22:08:10
Subject: @{b}Re: An idea for screen/window/gadget usage@{ub}

Hi Barnaky,

> >Sorry, to use the GTGadPtr(0,1,1) you need to use my updated gtlib.
>
> I will so, thanks! (Guess you mean the one named blitzgtfix.lha)

Yes.

> To avoid to be confused by all things that must be counted at a 'simple'
> window/gadget usage (bordersize, fontsize, etc) I want to declare a
> so-called 'Global Screen Environment Variable' named eg. GSEV (it's on
> my mind only this time but I'm starting to describe it). I imagined a
> form like this:

> NEWTYPE.GSEV
>   wtb.w ; window top border
>   wbb.w ; window bottom border
>   wlb.w ; window left border
>   wtb.w ; window right border
>   wfw.b ; window font with
>   wfh.b ; window font height
> End NEWTYPE
> DEFTYPE.GSEV TheScreen

From a personal point of view (because I use OS things directly a lot of 
the time), it might be useful to get pointers to things like the DrawInfo 
and VisualInfo for a screen and store it in the srtucture.  

> Function.b A_Screen{<screen's parameter>}
>   Shared TheScreen
>   Screen <parameters>
>   *scr._Screen=Peek.l(Addr Screen(SN))
>   wtb=scr\WBorderTop + ... <the font size + 1, don't remember the form>
>   <set other values>
> End Function

Rather than do it like this, you'd probably want the function to be 
something like:

Function.b A_Screen{*scdat.GSEV, <screen parameters>}
...
End Function

This would mean you wouldn't be tied to using a single global variable for 
the screen data. Another problem is that Blitz can only handle 6 parameters 
to functions (perhaps something AmiBlitz could fix :). Screens tend to need 
a lot of parameters, so perhaps you'd be better off passing a taglist as 
the parameters parameter ;)

You'd also be better off using ScreenTags instead of Screen to open your 
screen.

-- 
