@ENDNODE

@NODE "mail_229" " Picasso96 & VWait "
From: Thilo Köhler <koehlerthilo@...>
Date: 11-06-01 23:06:57
Subject: @{b}Picasso96 & VWait@{ub}

Hi all !

I noticed that some programs written in Blitz
slow down GFX output like refreshing Gadgets &
Windowborders under Picasso96 dramatically
so that they are unusable.

Now I have tracked this problem down to the
VWait command. So I come to this conclusion:

YOU SHOULD NEVER USE "VWAIT" IN A
SYSTEM FRIENDLY PROGRAM!

So far so good. But now I have a problem:

I have a program that should do some graphical
output like a audio-scope that has to be updated
in regular intervals, say 50 Hz. I used to do
this with a VWait statement to give CPU focus
to other programms after the drawings. But
how to do this without VWait in the system friendly 
way ? Any ideas ?

If heared that "delay_ 1" is a better but also not a 
very good idea. 

Greetings,

Thilo



---------------------------------------------------------------------
@ENDNODE

@NODE "mail_230" " Re: Picasso96 & VWait "
From: Robert Cranley <robertcranley@...>
Date: 11-06-01 23:14:13
Subject: @{b}Re: Picasso96 & VWait@{ub}

Hi Thilo,

On 06-Nov-01, you wrote:

> Now I have tracked this problem down to the
> VWait command. So I come to this conclusion:

> YOU SHOULD NEVER USE "VWAIT" IN A
> SYSTEM FRIENDLY PROGRAM!

True, it's tied into the native chipset, so programs using it still stick to
the 50Hz/60Hz speed, not the much higher speeds afforded by gfx boards.

> I have a program that should do some graphical
> output like a audio-scope that has to be updated
> in regular intervals, say 50 Hz. I used to do
> this with a VWait statement to give CPU focus
> to other programms after the drawings. But
> how to do this without VWait in the system friendly 
> way ? Any ideas ?

> If heared that "delay_ 1" is a better but also not a 
> very good idea. 

What about setting up an interrupt with a counter? Like


SetInt 5
  cc+1
End SetInt

That should still run at 50/60Hz (depending on PAL/NTSC) and *shouldn't*
affect the video update speed. Oh, and every time cc reaches its required
number of pulses, it should be reset to 0 :)

Regards,
    Rob
-- 
http://ireland.amiga.org

