@NODE "mail_268" " Searching for Double Precision Floating Point support "
From: Paul Richer <Paul.Richer@...>
Date: 11-28-01 07:04:07
Subject: @{b}Searching for Double Precision Floating Point support@{ub}

Hi guys!

I need big precision for a complex 3D lenticular printing software. I just found that many arithmetic functions return single precision floating point, destroying all my efforts for keeping enough precision with 32bit integer.

So I decided to switch to DPFP, or even better to Extended Precision Floating Point (80bit) if I can. But I didn't find any support library to convert from/to packed decimal binary or from/to string.

Any suggestions for easy hi-precision with Blitz?

Paul Richer
@ENDNODE

@NODE "mail_269" " Re: Searching for Double Precision Floating Point support "
From: "DAVID MCMINN (9429210)" <9429210@...>
Date: 11-28-01 10:59:31
Subject: @{b}Re: Searching for Double Precision Floating Point support@{ub}

Hi Paul

> So I decided to switch to DPFP, or even better to Extended Precision
> Floating Point (80bit) if I can. But I didn't find any support library
to
> convert from/to packed decimal binary or from/to string.

What's the format of a packed decimal number?

> Any suggestions for easy hi-precision with Blitz?

You could have a look at the FPUlib, from Aminet. It might support the
higher precision floating point values, or maybe it just uses the FPU
for Blitz's float type, I can't remember.

---------------------------------------------------------------------
@ENDNODE

@NODE "mail_270" " Re: Searching for Double Precision Floating Point support "
From: Bernd Roesch <berndroesch1@...>
Date: 11-28-01 10:49:51
Subject: @{b}Re: Searching for Double Precision Floating Point support@{ub}

That is not easy to implement because a new datatype 64bit must introduce and i need it not so this come not from me .Maybee you can use the inline assembler(it support 64bit fpu).You can then write your code in basic compile it and if it run copy the assembler lines and change the fmove.s to fmove.d. Make sure that your newtype have a additional 32bit entry for the other 32bit


